# Security Review

## Vulnerability 1

### Description

Credentials are hardcoded directly into the source code.

---

### Impact

Anyone with access to the source code can immediately view the credentials.

This increases the risk of unauthorized access if the code is exposed through version control, backups, or accidental disclosure.

---

### Severity

🔴 High

---

## Vulnerability 2

### Description

Passwords are stored in plain text.

---

### Impact

If the application or source code is compromised, attackers can read the password directly without any additional effort.

---

### Severity

🔴 Critical

---

## Vulnerability 3

### Description

No account lockout or rate limiting is implemented.

---

### Impact

Attackers can repeatedly attempt different passwords without restriction, increasing the risk of brute-force attacks.

---

### Severity

🟠 Medium

---

## Vulnerability 4

### Description

The function performs simple string comparison without integrating with a secure authentication system.

---

### Impact

The implementation is not suitable for production use because it lacks support for secure credential storage, user management, and authentication workflows.

---

### Severity

🟡 Medium

---

# Risk Assessment

